The caller's composure, vocabulary, and the details they volunteer must match this persona. A terrified parent sounds different from a trained teacher. The dispatcher's instructions while waiting must be grounded only in the reference text.

---
GENERATION RULES — follow every rule exactly:

CONVERSATION STRUCTURE:
  Turn 1 (caller): Calls in a panic. Gives location and broad emergency. Does not know exactly what to say.
  Turn 2 (dispatcher): Confirms location. Asks the single most critical triage question (conscious? breathing?).
  Turn 3 (caller): Answers. May give conflicting or incomplete information typical of a panicked caller.
  Turn 4 (dispatcher): Clarifies if needed. Confirms ambulance is dispatched. Begins coaching first aid steps — one at a time — only from the reference text.
  Turn 5+ : Dispatcher continues coaching step by step. Caller reports back what they see. Continue until ambulance arrives or procedure is complete.
  FINAL dispatcher turn: Tells caller what to expect when ambulance arrives, and what NOT to do.

DISPATCHER RULES:
  a. Always confirm location in the first response.
  b. Deliver first aid instructions one step at a time — never a list dump.
  c. All first aid instructions must come ONLY from the reference text.
  d. Stay calm, direct, no filler words ("Great!", "Perfect!").
  e. If ETA is long, prioritize the most critical action and explicitly tell the caller help is X minutes away.

CALLER RULES:
  a. Caller sounds scared. May speak in fragments.
  b. Caller may initially omit key details (victim's age, exact location, whether they're breathing).
  c. Caller must confirm back each step they carry out — don't just go silent.

SKIP RULE: If the reference text has no actionable first aid procedure — output only:
{% raw %}{"skip": true, "reason": "<one sentence reason>"}{% endraw %}

